<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-058-522  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 058 522.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications of the ACM  Feb 1989 v32 n2 p274(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Assn. for Computing Machinery, Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Nova University and ErrorNot isolate particular computer virus.andO;(general news) (technical)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT/><NOTE>Only Text is presented here; see printed issues for graphics.andO;</NOTE><TEXT>Nova University and Error Not Isolate Particular Computer Virus Ahardware-induced computer virus could potentially affect 25 millionmicrocomputers, according to a recent discovery by researchers at NovaUniversity and ErrorNot Corporation.andM;The researchers say the virus is the result of faulty programming in themicrocode of a device used in computers.andP;  Research indicates this viruscauses data corruption, and its random pattern of attack with small datadestruction makes it difficult to identify.andP;  The virus's dormancy periodvaries from weeks or months to even years.andM;Nova University's Computer Science Department has assembled the results ofits findings (TR-881101-1) and a risk-assessment program that helps usersdetermine their susceptibility to the virus.andP;  Both are available on a diskfor $5 from Dr. Edward R. Simco, Dean, Computer Science Department, 3301College Avenue, Fort Lauderdale, FL 33314; (305) 475-7563.andM;The researchers at ErrorNot Corporation have created a slotless device theysay is effective in eliminating the virus.andP;  For more information, contactWilliam R. Griffin, President, ErrorNot Corporation, 3200 North FederalHighway, Suite 120, Boca Raton, FL 33431; (407) 395-2306.andO;</TEXT></DOC>